Matplotlib 

1ï¸) What is Matplotlib?

Pythonâ€™s basic plotting library.
Helps turn numbers into pictures (graphs, charts).
Think of it as Excel charts but with Python control.
Seaborn, Pandas .plot() â†’ all built on top of Matplotlib.



2ï¸) Importing

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
pyplot is the submodule used for plotting. Most people use plt as alias.

3ï¸) Basic Workflow

Every plot follows this flow:
Prepare data
Call plt.plot() (or other chart functions)
Customize (labels, title, colors)
Show â†’ plt.show()


4ï¸) Types of Plots

ğŸ”¹ Line Plot
x = [1,2,3,4,5]
y = [2,4,6,8,10]
plt.plot(x, y, color="red", linestyle="--", marker="o")
plt.title("Line Plot")
plt.xlabel("X Axis")
plt.ylabel("Y Axis")
plt.show()

ğŸ”¹ Bar Chart
categories = ["A", "B", "C"]
values = [10, 20, 15]
plt.bar(categories, values, color="purple")
plt.title("Bar Chart")
plt.show()

ğŸ”¹ Histogram
import numpy as np
data = np.random.randn(1000)  # 1000 random numbers
plt.hist(data, bins=30, color="skyblue", edgecolor="black")
plt.title("Histogram")
plt.show()

ğŸ”¹ Scatter Plot
x = np.random.rand(50)
y = np.random.rand(50)
plt.scatter(x, y, color="green")
plt.title("Scatter Plot")
plt.show()

ğŸ”¹ Box Plot (Whisker Plot)
data = np.random.randn(100)
plt.boxplot(data)
plt.title("Box Plot")
plt.show()

ğŸ”¹ Pie Chart
sizes = [30, 20, 50]
labels = ["Apples", "Bananas", "Cherries"]
plt.pie(sizes, labels=labels, autopct="%1.1f%%")
plt.title("Pie Chart")
plt.show()

5ï¸) Customization Options
ğŸ”¹ Titles & Labels
plt.title("My Chart")
plt.xlabel("X Label")
plt.ylabel("Y Label")

ğŸ”¹ Legends
plt.plot(x, y, label="Line 1")
plt.legend()

ğŸ”¹ Grid
plt.grid(True)

ğŸ”¹ Figure Size
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))

ğŸ”¹ Multiple Plots (Subplots)
plt.subplot(1,2,1)  # row=1, col=2, index=1
plt.plot(x,y)
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.bar(categories, values)
plt.show()

6ï¸) Object-Oriented Interface (Pro Way)

Instead of plt.plot(), you create a figure + axes.
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6,4))
ax.plot(x, y, color="red")
ax.set_title("Line Plot")
ax.set_xlabel("X axis")
ax.set_ylabel("Y axis")
plt.show()

7ï¸) Pandas + Matplotlib Shortcut

Pandas DataFrames have .plot() which internally uses Matplotlib.
import pandas as pd
df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1,2,3,4], "B": [10,20,15,30]})
df.plot(kind="bar")
plt.show()

8ï¸) Best Practices

Always label axes + title â†’ otherwise graph = meaningless.
Choose the right chart type:
Trend â†’ Line
Compare categories â†’ Bar
Distribution â†’ Histogram
Relationship â†’ Scatter
Outliers â†’ Box
Proportions â†’ Pie



Quick Summary

plt.plot() â†’ Line plots
plt.bar() â†’ Bars
plt.hist() â†’ Histograms
plt.scatter() â†’ Scatter plots
plt.boxplot() â†’ Outliers
plt.pie() â†’ Proportions
plt.subplot() â†’ Multiple plots
plt.show() â†’ Display final graph
